---
export const prerender = true;
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---
<Base title="process" miscTitle="process" showAnnouncement={false}>
  <article class="doc">
    <header class="doc__head">
      <p class="doc__kicker">// case study &middot; graphic design</p>
      <h1 class="doc__title">the process.</h1>
      <p class="doc__lede">
        Notes on where the palette, the type, and the visual language came from.
        Nothing here is finalised; the point of a process page is to show the reasoning,
        not to sell it.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="sec">
      <p class="sec__num">01</p>
      <h2 class="sec__h">palette</h2>
      <p>
        Cream first, not white. I print on satin card stock, and monitor white blows out sitting
        next to a physical print of the same design. So the site backgrounds match the paper
        (#fdfcf9, #f5f4f0). The catalog is meant to feel like a real object, not a screenshot of one.
      </p>
      <p>
        Slate-violet (#5061b9) is pulled from the blue in Yuzuha's uniform. Cold enough to work as
        a system UI colour, warm enough that it doesn't read as a raw hex value. Every neutral
        page runs on it &mdash; it's the accent, the link colour, the sticky bar background.
      </p>
      <p>
        The yellow (#ffee00) is the same yellow as the SOLD OUT tape convention artists slap on
        empty prints. Loud, unmixed, deliberately close to CMYK-limit yellow. Only used for
        callouts and highlights. If you fill anything larger than a chip with it, it eats the page.
      </p>
      <p>
        The graphic-design section swaps to a dark cinema pair (#0d0c13 to #14131a). Character
        illustration reads best against near-black; full #000 was too violent next to the cream
        everywhere else, so the section blends into a very dark neutral instead.
      </p>
      <p>
        The two pinks (#ff4da6, #fd7ac0) only exist inside the PSG and NSO themed rooms. They'd
        ruin the neutral pages if they escaped, but they carry the whole personality of those two
        drops when the walls close in around them.
      </p>
      <div class="swatches">
        <div class="sw"><span style="background: #fdfcf9; border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.14)"></span>#fdfcf9 cream</div>
        <div class="sw"><span style="background: #14131a"></span>#14131a ink</div>
        <div class="sw"><span style="background: #5061b9"></span>#5061b9 slate-violet</div>
        <div class="sw"><span style="background: #ffee00; border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.14)"></span>#ffee00 tape yellow</div>
        <div class="sw"><span style="background: #0d0c13"></span>#0d0c13 cinema</div>
        <div class="sw"><span style="background: #ff4da6"></span>#ff4da6 psg pink</div>
        <div class="sw"><span style="background: #fd7ac0"></span>#fd7ac0 nso magenta</div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sec">
      <p class="sec__num">02</p>
      <h2 class="sec__h">typography</h2>
      <p>
        Titles, labels, and navigation are set in Apex Mk3, a monospace face. Most copy on the
        site is short strings: product names, prices, section numbers, timestamps. Monospace makes
        those feel tabular and intentional, not casual. It also ties the design side of the site
        to the infra side &mdash; the ops pages under /status, /cost, and /architecture use the
        same face, so both halves of the portfolio read as one voice.
      </p>
      <p>
        Body copy is Branding Pro. Wide x-height, five weights, quiet next to the mono headers.
        It does the work you don't notice, which is exactly the job.
      </p>
      <p>
        One line per section, usually the eyebrow, is set in Beam Visionary &mdash; a script
        italic. It's there specifically to break the machine feel. One line of a human hand, then
        back to the terminal. Used sparingly on purpose; if it appeared more than once per screen
        it would stop working.
      </p>
      <p>
        The NSO room runs on NSO CRT, an actual bitmap font. Chyrons, popup labels, HUD text.
        It doesn't appear anywhere else. The themed rooms are supposed to feel like walking into
        separate shops with separate identities; swapping the entire typeface is the fastest way
        to signal you've stepped into a different one.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid--2">
        <div class="face">
          <p class="face__name">Apex Mk3</p>
          <p class="face__sample" style="font-family: 'Apex Mk3', monospace;">.contact</p>
          <p class="face__role">Mono. Titles, labels, nav, ops pages.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="face">
          <p class="face__name">Branding Pro</p>
          <p class="face__sample" style="font-family: 'Branding Pro', sans-serif;">Body copy &mdash; running text.</p>
          <p class="face__role">Sans. Body. Five weights. Wide x-height.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="face">
          <p class="face__name">Beam Visionary</p>
          <p class="face__sample" style="font-family: 'Beam Visionary', cursive; font-style: italic;">from the desk.</p>
          <p class="face__role">Script italic. One eyebrow per section, no more.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="face">
          <p class="face__name">NSO CRT</p>
          <p class="face__sample" style="font-family: 'NSO CRT', monospace; letter-spacing: 0.06em;">SIGNAL &gt; NO SYNC</p>
          <p class="face__role">Pixel bitmap. NSO themed room only.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sec">
      <p class="sec__num">03</p>
      <h2 class="sec__h">inspirations</h2>
      <p>
        Not a moodboard. These are the specific pieces I kept re-opening while working on the
        site, and what I took from each.
      </p>
      <ul class="inspo">
        <li>
          <p class="inspo__name">Arknights: Endfield &mdash; promotional site.</p>
          <p>Nested HUD widgets, transparent overlay panels, extremely comfortable being visually
            dense. The graphic and photo sections here inherit that willingness to layer decor over
            content.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p class="inspo__name">Panty &amp; Stocking with Garterbelt &mdash; DVD liner notes.</p>
          <p>Halftone dots, hot pink frills, Y2K collage energy. Lifted wholesale for the PSG
            themed room. The tilted cyan slab and card-stack showcase are direct references.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p class="inspo__name">Needy Streamer Overload.</p>
          <p>CRT scanlines, RGB-glitching popups, chrome desktop backdrop. The NSO themed room
            in one line. The alerts, the popups, the intentionally decayed UI &mdash; it's all
            from that game.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p class="inspo__name">Convention artist alley table cards.</p>
          <p>The little "01 / 20" numbered chip and the stock indicator on every product card came
            from watching how table sellers label runs. It reads at a glance and it makes finite
            drops feel finite.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p class="inspo__name">Muji product catalogs.</p>
          <p>How they set a large product photo next to a tiny mono label without either fighting
            the other. The catalog page owes them the whole layout: photo, monospace label,
            hairline rule, price. Nothing else.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p class="inspo__name">Ghost in the Shell &mdash; the 1995 film's opening credits.</p>
          <p>Where the terminal-monospace eyebrow above every section came from. Katakana-style
            numeric prefixes, thin rules, everything in a small caps mono. Not literally copied,
            but the mood is unavoidable.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="sec sec--cta">
      <p class="sec__cta-kicker">// next</p>
      <h2 class="sec__cta-h">how it ships &rarr;</h2>
      <p>
        The whole storefront runs on a serverless AWS stack.
        <a href="/architecture/">Walk through the infrastructure</a> or
        <a href="/catalog/">browse the catalog</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>

  <style>
    .doc { max-width: 820px; margin: 0 auto; padding: clamp(48px, 8vw, 96px) clamp(24px, 6vw, 48px); }
    .doc__head { margin-bottom: 8vh; }
    .doc__kicker {
      font-family: 'Apex Mk3', 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.22em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--misc-accent, #5061b9);
      margin: 0 0 20px;
    }
    .doc__title {
      font-family: 'Apex Mk3', sans-serif;
      font-weight: 300;
      font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 5vw, 3.6rem);
      line-height: 1;
      margin: 0 0 24px;
      text-transform: lowercase;
    }
    .doc__lede {
      font-family: 'Branding Pro', sans-serif;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      line-height: 1.55;
      color: var(--misc-ink-soft, #6b6b6b);
      margin: 0;
      max-width: 620px;
    }
    .sec { margin-bottom: 8vh; }
    .sec__num {
      font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.22em;
      color: var(--misc-accent, #5061b9);
      margin: 0 0 6px;
    }
    .sec__h {
      font-family: 'Apex Mk3', sans-serif;
      font-weight: 400;
      font-size: 1.4rem;
      color: var(--misc-ink, #1a1a1a);
      margin: 0 0 20px;
      padding-bottom: 12px;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--misc-line, rgba(0,0,0,0.14));
      text-transform: lowercase;
    }
    .sec p, .sec li { font-family: 'Branding Pro', sans-serif; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 16px; color: var(--misc-ink); }
    .grid { display: grid; gap: 20px; margin-top: 20px; }
    .grid--2 { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
    .face {
      padding: 20px;
      background: #fff;
      border: 1px solid var(--misc-line, rgba(0,0,0,0.14));
      clip-path: polygon(0 0, calc(100% - 10px) 0, 100% 10px, 100% 100%, 0 100%);
    }
    .face__name {
      font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
      font-size: 0.68rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.18em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--misc-accent, #5061b9);
      margin: 0 0 10px;
    }
    .face__role { font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0; color: var(--misc-ink-soft); }
    .face__sample { font-size: 1.5rem; margin: 4px 0 14px; line-height: 1.1; color: var(--misc-ink); }
    .swatches { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(160px, 1fr)); gap: 12px; margin-top: 24px; }
    .sw { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 10px; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--misc-ink-soft); }
    .sw span { display: inline-block; width: 26px; height: 26px; border: 1px solid var(--misc-line); }
    .inspo { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 20px 0 0; }
    .inspo li { margin: 0 0 22px; padding: 16px 0 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--misc-line, rgba(0,0,0,0.14)); }
    .inspo li:first-child { border-top: none; padding-top: 0; }
    .inspo__name {
      font-family: 'Apex Mk3', sans-serif;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      font-weight: 400;
      color: var(--misc-ink);
      margin: 0 0 6px;
    }
    .inspo li p:last-child { margin: 0; color: var(--misc-ink-soft); font-size: 0.95rem; }
    .sec--cta { padding: 28px; background: rgba(80, 97, 185, 0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(80,97,185,0.14); clip-path: polygon(0 0, calc(100% - 14px) 0, 100% 14px, 100% 100%, 0 100%); }
    .sec__cta-kicker {
      font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.22em;
      color: var(--misc-accent);
      margin: 0 0 8px;
    }
    .sec__cta-h { font-family: 'Apex Mk3', sans-serif; font-size: 1.6rem; margin: 0 0 12px; font-weight: 300; text-transform: lowercase; }
    .sec--cta p { margin: 0; }
    .sec--cta a { color: var(--misc-accent); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; }
    @media (max-width: 700px) {
      .grid--2 { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    }
  </style>
</Base>
